about how you deal

00:30:50.030 --> 00:30:52.220
with system bars, like the
Status bar and the Navigation

00:30:52.220 --> 00:30:55.750
bar, where your content is
supposed to be immersive.

00:30:55.750 --> 00:30:58.810
So for example, photos, videos,
or books, or things

00:30:58.810 --> 00:30:59.910
like that as you're reading.

00:30:59.910 --> 00:31:01.900
So very quickly, just a
couple of definitions.

00:31:01.900 --> 00:31:05.210
You have the status bar, which
contains notifications as well

00:31:05.210 --> 00:31:07.370
as time and date--

00:31:07.370 --> 00:31:11.150
well, not date, but time as well
as battery level, WiFi,

00:31:11.150 --> 00:31:12.500
cell signal, things like that.

00:31:12.500 --> 00:31:15.840
That's the Status bar,
just for terminology.

00:31:15.840 --> 00:31:19.130
The Navigation bar is the bar
at the bottom that contains

00:31:19.130 --> 00:31:20.970
Back, Home, and Recent.

00:31:20.970 --> 00:31:22.890
On earlier versions of the
platform, you don't actually

00:31:22.890 --> 00:31:23.900
have a Navigation bar.

00:31:23.900 --> 00:31:26.540
Because you have, I
guess, soft keys.

00:31:26.540 --> 00:31:28.230
I never know if you should
call them soft

00:31:28.230 --> 00:31:29.510
keys or hard keys.

00:31:29.510 --> 00:31:32.840
You have keys that are built
into the device for that.

00:31:32.840 --> 00:31:35.540
So the Navigation bar is
something that appears on

00:31:35.540 --> 00:31:41.110
newer devices that don't have
any sort of keys on the front.

00:31:41.110 --> 00:31:43.642
And just in terms of sizes,
for designers, you should

00:31:43.642 --> 00:31:45.480
obviously care about the
size of these things.

00:31:45.480 --> 00:31:47.050
They can vary from
device to device.

00:31:47.050 --> 00:31:48.380
There's no single standard.

00:31:48.380 --> 00:31:51.390
And this fits in with, don't
design for one pixel

00:31:51.390 --> 00:31:51.910
resolution.

00:31:51.910 --> 00:31:54.650
But in case you are interested,
roughly, in

00:31:54.650 --> 00:31:57.380
general, the Status bar
is about 25 dips tall.

00:31:57.380 --> 00:32:00.130
And the Navigation bar
is about 48 dips.

00:32:00.130 --> 00:32:02.940
I think on phones in landscape,
it's actually a lot

00:32:02.940 --> 00:32:04.760
smaller, like 40 dips.

00:32:04.760 --> 00:32:06.460
And again, don't rely
on these numbers.

00:32:06.460 --> 00:32:08.500
These are numbers that will
probably change in the future.

00:32:08.500 --> 00:32:11.950
And they'll probably change
on different devices.

00:32:11.950 --> 00:32:14.200
On earlier versions of the
platform, there was this

00:32:14.200 --> 00:32:17.820
combined bar that combined both
the Status bar and the

00:32:17.820 --> 00:32:19.920
Navigation elements.

00:32:19.920 --> 00:32:22.760
And this was also generally
48 dips tall.

00:32:22.760 --> 00:32:24.400
But this is more deprecated.

00:32:24.400 --> 00:32:28.190
So if you see screen shots,
especially, with this, they're

00:32:28.190 --> 00:32:32.360
using the older system
UI style.

00:32:32.360 --> 00:32:34.440
So make sure that you
plan for both.

00:32:34.440 --> 00:32:38.100
Because if you're supporting,
for example, Android 4.0--

00:32:38.100 --> 00:32:38.820
actually, it was 4.0?

00:32:38.820 --> 00:32:39.040
Yes.

00:32:39.040 --> 00:32:40.430
4.0 was using this.

00:32:40.430 --> 00:32:43.380
If you're supporting Android 4.0
and higher, be aware that

00:32:43.380 --> 00:32:47.150
your notifications may actually
be on the bottom

00:32:47.150 --> 00:32:49.280
right at some point.

00:32:49.280 --> 00:32:50.090
OK.

00:32:50.090 --> 00:32:52.340
So there are lots of different
full screen modes.

00:32:52.340 --> 00:32:55.100
And this slide is littered
with stuff.

00:32:55.100 --> 00:32:57.140
But you basically have
a couple of modes.

00:32:57.140 --> 00:32:59.410
You have Normal Mode, where
everything is visible.

00:32:59.410 --> 00:33:02.680
You have Low Profile mode, where
the bars are visible.

00:33:02.680 --> 00:33:06.340
And actually, you can
selectively mix and match what

00:33:06.340 --> 00:33:09.120
happens to the status bar
and navigation bar.

00:33:09.120 --> 00:33:12.750
But the Low Profile mode still
shows the bars, but it recedes

00:33:12.750 --> 00:33:13.730
them visually.

00:33:13.730 --> 00:33:17.270
So you'll notice that the status
bar here is dimmed.

00:33:17.270 --> 00:33:19.050
You actually don't even see
the notification icon.

00:33:19.050 --> 00:33:22.270
You see just a little dot
indicating that there's

00:33:22.270 --> 00:33:23.560
something there.

00:33:23.560 --> 00:33:25.170
And then your Back, Home,
and Recents are

00:33:25.170 --> 00:33:26.710
also visually recessed.

00:33:26.710 --> 00:33:30.830
So they're also just little
dots, hinting to the user

00:33:30.830 --> 00:33:32.290
that, hey, there's
something here.

00:33:32.290 --> 00:33:35.690
It's not completely
non-interactive, but touch

00:33:35.690 --> 00:33:37.200
here to find out.

00:33:37.200 --> 00:33:39.060
And then a couple of points.

00:33:39.060 --> 00:33:40.810
Generally, when you use this
kind of UI, something that

00:33:40.810 --> 00:33:43.160
works really well is overlaying
the Action bar.

00:33:43.160 --> 00:33:46.560
So here, this is actually
the Action Bar with a

00:33:46.560 --> 00:33:50.320
semi-transparency applied.

00:33:50.320 --> 00:33:53.190
Another important point is, when
you touch on the content,

00:33:53.190 --> 00:33:54.430
you should always toggle.

00:33:54.430 --> 00:33:54.630
Right?

00:33:54.630 --> 00:33:57.600
So you should never permanently
be in Low Profile

00:33:57.600 --> 00:33:59.910
Mode or this other mode,
which we'll talk about.

00:33:59.910 --> 00:34:02.320
So touching should actually
be the action

00:34:02.320 --> 00:34:03.570
that toggles things.

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:08.070
And actually, in this Low
Profile Mode, you obviously

00:34:08.070 --> 00:34:10.710
also want to hide other
UI elements as well

00:34:10.710 --> 00:34:12.030
as the action bar.

00:34:12.030 --> 00:34:12.820
That's actually one
thing I should

00:34:12.820 --> 00:34:14.790
mention right after this.

00:34:14.790 --> 00:34:17.449
So there's another mode called
Hide Navigation.

00:34:17.449 --> 00:34:20.949
And Hide Navigation hides the
Navigation Bar at the bottom.

00:34:20.949 --> 00:34:26.360
And it usually also hides the
top bar, the Status Bar.

00:34:26.360 --> 00:34:29.020
So in this case, you have
full control over the

00:34:29.020 --> 00:34:30.150
pixels on the screen.

00:34:30.150 --> 00:34:31.590
So basically, your
app is drawing

00:34:31.590 --> 00:34:32.520
everything to the screen.

00:34:32.520 --> 00:34:36.159
And this works really well
for video content.

00:34:36.159 --> 00:34:39.590
And one caveat here is that
this isn't permanent.

00:34:39.590 --> 00:34:43.127
As soon as the user touches the
screen, the system will

00:34:43.127 --> 00:34:44.870
automatically show the
navigation again.

00:34:44.870 --> 00:34:47.500
Because you don't want to lock
the user into a place where

00:34:47.500 --> 00:34:49.489
they have no access to Back,
Home, and Recents.

00:34:49.489 --> 00:34:52.130
That's just really,
really bad.

00:34:52.130 --> 00:34:54.400
So there's one thing I
wanted to mention.

00:34:54.400 --> 00:34:55.230
Oh, right.

00:34:55.230 --> 00:34:57.250
The last thing I wanted to
mention about these different

00:34:57.250 --> 00:35:02.000
modes is, you generally want
to only switch between two,

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:03.520
Normal and Low Profile.

00:35:03.520 --> 00:35:05.430
Or Normal and Hide Navigation.

00:35:05.430 --> 00:35:08.380
And you don't want to have
different UI elements on the

00:35:08.380 --> 00:35:10.730
screen going on and off
at different times.

00:35:10.730 --> 00:35:13.570
You actually want to make sure
that you either have the

00:35:13.570 --> 00:35:16.462
Status Bar, the Navigation Bar,
the Action Bar, and all

00:35:16.462 --> 00:35:19.720
of the other UI controls all
visible, like here, or none of

00:35:19.720 --> 00:35:20.790
them visible.

00:35:20.790 --> 00:35:23.270
So basically, this boils down
to, make sure that the Action

00:35:23.270 --> 00:35:26.930
Bar visibility is tied to the
visibility of the other

00:35:26.930 --> 00:35:27.980
elements of the screen.

00:35:27.980 --> 00:35:29.680
ADAM KOCH: The way I like to
think about this, too, is that

00:35:29.680 --> 00:35:32.190
Low Profile is for an immersive
activity where there

00:35:32.190 --> 00:35:33.990
may still be some user
interaction.

00:35:33.990 --> 00:35:36.250
Like maybe you're swiping
through photos.

00:35:36.250 --> 00:35:38.350
Maybe you're reading a book
or something like that.

00:35:38.350 --> 00:35:40.800
Whereas the Hide Navigation is
more useful for something

00:35:40.800 --> 00:35:42.150
where you're not interacting
with it.

00:35:42.150 --> 00:35:42.930
Like watching video.

00:35:42.930 --> 00:35:44.980
You're sitting back and
looking at the screen.

00:35:44.980 --> 00:35:45.840
ROMAN NURIK: Exactly.

00:35:45.840 --> 00:35:46.980
Exactly.

00:35:46.980 --> 00:35:47.400
OK.

00:35:47.400 --> 00:35:49.170
So those are the different
modes.

00:35:49.170 --> 00:35:52.450
Just a couple of examples on
apps that do this, in our

00:35:52.450 --> 00:35:53.470
opinion, really well.

00:35:53.470 --> 00:35:54.920
First is Google Play Books.

00:35:54.920 --> 00:36:01.400
So by default, you see your
actual book itself, as well as

00:36:01.400 --> 00:36:04.850
some controls at the bottom, and
the action bar at the top.

00:36:04.850 --> 00:36:06.950
But as soon as you touch--

00:36:06.950 --> 00:36:07.890
well, actually, not here.

00:36:07.890 --> 00:36:11.190
As soon as you touch the screen,
the Action Bar, the

00:36:11.190 --> 00:36:16.700
Status Bar, and the UI control
at the bottom, the Scrubber,

00:36:16.700 --> 00:36:17.870
they all fade out.

00:36:17.870 --> 00:36:20.520
And then the Navigation Bar goes
into Low Profile Mode.

00:36:20.520 --> 00:36:24.430
So what you end up seeing
is nothing but content.

00:36:24.430 --> 00:36:27.310
Nothing but the body
of the book itself.

00:36:27.310 --> 00:36:29.450
And then there are some actions
here for Back, Home,

00:36:29.450 --> 00:36:30.420
and Recents, obviously.

00:36:30.420 --> 00:36:32.150
Those should be visible.

00:36:32.150 --> 00:36:34.660
Another nice thing that this
does is that the content

00:36:34.660 --> 00:36:35.760
doesn't jump.

00:36:35.760 --> 00:36:40.520
So if I touch to toggle, the
content doesn't realign itself

00:36:40.520 --> 00:36:42.150
or re-lay itself out.

00:36:42.150 --> 00:36:44.660
And this is possible
on Jellybean.

00:36:44.660 --> 00:36:48.090
So in Jellybean, we introduced
some new APIs to make sure

00:36:48.090 --> 00:36:49.350
that this is possible.

00:36:49.350 --> 00:36:51.940
On earlier versions, it's much
harder to do that if you're

00:36:51.940 --> 00:36:54.440
showing and hiding certain
things, like the Navigation

00:36:54.440 --> 00:36:56.090
Bar especially.

00:36:56.090 --> 00:36:58.310
Another app that does this
really well is Pocket.

00:36:58.310 --> 00:37:01.230
So they're also a reading app.

00:37:01.230 --> 00:37:05.920
But one thing that they've do
slightly differently is, they

00:37:05.920 --> 00:37:07.330
also toggle on touch.

00:37:07.330 --> 00:37:12.870
But they also hide the system
UI as you start scrolling.

00:37:12.870 --> 00:37:14.740
So as you start scrolling
down, it goes

00:37:14.740 --> 00:37:16.060
into Low Profile Mode.

00:37:16.060 --> 00:37:17.890
It still shows the status
bar, which is good.

00:37:17.890 --> 00:37:20.940
Because if you have an email
come in, you want to be aware

00:37:20.940 --> 00:37:23.300
that something is happening.

00:37:23.300 --> 00:37:27.260
And also, it shows Low Profile
Mode for the Navigation Bar.

00:37:27.260 --> 00:37:29.050
So it's really, really subtle.

00:37:29.050 --> 00:37:32.960
But it's very nice to let the
user really focus on the

00:37:32.960 --> 00:37:35.510
content itself.

00:37:35.510 --> 00:37:37.820
And lastly we have YouTube.

00:37:37.820 --> 00:37:40.490
So YouTube is the canonical
example of a great

00:37:40.490 --> 00:37:43.290
video-playing application.

00:37:43.290 --> 00:37:46.060
And obviously, what YouTube
is, they hide everything

00:37:46.060 --> 00:37:49.610
possible when you go into
this full screen mode.

00:37:49.610 --> 00:37:54.900
So this is, again, possible with
the new Jellybean APIs.

00:37:54.900 --> 00:37:58.370
And, oh, one thing to note is
that, in the new Jellybean

00:37:58.370 --> 00:38:02.260
API, one of the caveats, or
consequences is that the

00:38:02.260 --> 00:38:04.830
Navigation Bar can actually
overlay your content.

00:38:04.830 --> 00:38:07.190
So you notice here that the
Navigation Bar is actually

00:38:07.190 --> 00:38:08.700
cutting off the content.

00:38:08.700 --> 00:38:10.610
So if you have something
really important at the

00:38:10.610 --> 00:38:12.640
bottom, or I guess in this
case at the right of your

00:38:12.640 --> 00:38:14.630
screen, you've got to make
sure that you're not

00:38:14.630 --> 00:38:15.940
necessarily using that flag.

00:38:15.940 --> 00:38:18.412
You probably just want
to use Low Profile.

